  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Example scripts of full-closure imaging\n",
    "What you will use are **uvdata**, **imdata**, **imaging** modules. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from smili import uvdata,imdata,imaging\n",
    "import numpy as np"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Load data\n",
    "First, you need to load the uvfits data into **uvdata.UVFITS** object."

   "source": [
    "uvfits = uvdata.UVFITS(\"3C273DEC16.UVP\")"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This data set is VLBA 43 GHz data of 3C 273 from the Boston University Blazar group. As you can see the above log, this data set has full Stokes parameters. A simple way to make Stokes I image is computing Stokes I visibilities using UVFITS.select_stokes method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 34,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Stokes I data will be calculated from input RR and LL data\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "uvfitsI = uvfits.select_stokes(stokes=\"I\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For imaging, SMILI use two dimensional data tables using classes inheriting **pandas.DataFrame**."

  },

   "source": [
    "# Create a table of full complex visibilities\n",
    "vistable = uvfitsI.make_vistable()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a table of bi-spectra\n",
    "bstable = vistable.make_bstable()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a table of closure amplitudes\n",
    "catable = vistable.make_catable()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can save these tables with .to_csv() methods in a similar way to pandas.DataFrame"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "vistable.to_csv(\"vistable.csv\")\n",
    "bstable.to_csv(\"bstable.csv\")\n",
    "catable.to_csv(\"catable.csv\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can read these tables with **uvdata.read_XXtable** functions. You probably don't need to recompute closure quanties onece they are formulated, so this save & load process can save your time for full closure imaging."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "vistable = uvdata.read_vistable(\"vistable.csv\")\n",
    "bstable = uvdata.read_bstable(\"bstable.csv\")\n",
    "catable = uvdata.read_catable(\"catable.csv\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Full Closure Imaging"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Here, we would try a simple imaging with full closure quantities and also error-increased amplitude data sets.\n",
    "Full closure imaging is non-convex optimization, so therefore the resultant image will be affected by a choise of the initial image. In particular, you need non-zero (not empty image) for closure imaging, since closure imaging do not have sensitivities in the absolute position and needs a reference for a relative position.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here, we can start from a circular Gaussian, of which beam size is corresponding to the minor beam size of the synthesized beam.\n",
    "You can estimate beam size parameters from vistable."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 36,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "{u'minsize': 0.09997702850886185, u'pa': 1.598749744843019, u'majsize': 0.2990026222862978, u'angunit': 'mas'}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "beamprm = vistable.fit_beam(angunit=\"mas\")\n",
    "print(beamprm)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can make a circular Gaussian of which size is same to the minor axis size of the beam."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 37,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "beamprm[\"majsize\"] = beamprm[\"minsize\"]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For starting imaging, we need to define the image FOV, pixel size. SMILI will do it by setting the initial image."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 38,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# This command can create an empty image. The final option uvfitsfile is optional, and can read header informations from uvfits file.\n",
    "initimage = imdata.IMFITS(dx=0.02, nx=256, ny=256, nxref=40, nyref=216, angunit=\"mas\", uvfitsfile=\"3C273DEC16.UVP\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# add a Gaussian\n",
    "initimage = initimage.add_gauss(totalflux=1, **beamprm) # this can add a circular or elliptical gaussian to the image\n",
    "\n",
    "# show imagee\n",
    "initimage.imshow(logscale=True,dyrange=100)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In interferometric imaging, limiting imaging region genrally works as a really nice prior if we have a reliable prior information for the source structure. SMILI has a function to set such a region with **imdata.IMRegion** object. To make a region table more flexiblly, please have a look at the instruction of IMRegion."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "region = imdata.IMRegion()\n",
    "region = region.add_box(xc=-2.0,yc=-2.0,width=7.0,height=2.0,angle=-45,angunit=\"mas\")\n",
    "\n",
    "initimage.imshow(angunit=\"mas\")\n",
    "region.plot(angunit=\"mas\",color=\"yellow\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before starting imaging, let's make a table for visibility amplitudes. Since they could have residual gain errors, let's add additional errors for residual errrors. We can copy tables for full complex visibilities and add potential systematic errors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "syserr = 0.2\n",
    "amptable = vistable.copy()\n",
    "amptable[\"sigma\"] = np.sqrt(np.square(amptable[\"sigma\"])+np.square(syserr * amptable[\"amp\"]))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Then, now is the time to make the first image! The simplest imaging function is imaging.lbfgs.imaging."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 41,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "imprm = {}\n",
    "imprm[\"amptable\"]=amptable # use amplitudes\n",
    "imprm[\"bstable\"]=bstable # use closure phases\n",
    "imprm[\"catable\"]=catable # use closure amplitudes\n",
    "imprm[\"lambl1\"]=1\n",
    "imprm[\"lambtsv\"]=0.1\n",
    "imprm[\"lambcom\"]=0.01\n",
    "imprm[\"compower\"]=3.0 # the power of the centroid. 1 gives the regularization using the exact center of the mass. The higher value gives regularization using the region close to the peak of the image.\n",
    "imprm[\"niter\"]=1000 # iteration number\n",
    "imprm[\"imregion\"]=region # imaging window"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 42,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Imaging Window: Specified. Images will be solved on specified pixels.\n",
      "Total Flux Constraint: disabled.\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "outimage = imaging.lbfgs.imaging(initimage,**imprm)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can check howthe image is."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "outimage.imshow(logscale=True,dyrange=100)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 49,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "outimage.save_fitsfits(\"3C273_image.fits\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can also see the statistical quantities (chisquares, reduced chisquares) with imaging.lbfgs.statistics"
   ]

   "execution_count": 44,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {

     "output_type": "stream",

      "Imaging Window: Specified. Images will be calcurated on specified pixels.\n",

   "source": [
    "imaging.lbfgs.statistics(outimage, **imprm)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "SMILI also provides a function to do some iterative procedure for imaging. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 45,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "imfargs = {}\n",
    "imfargs[\"Niter\"] = 3 # number of iterations\n",
    "imfargs[\"dothres\"] = True  # doing thresholding\n",
    "imfargs[\"threstype\"] = \"hard\" # type of thresholding (soft or hard)\n",
    "imfargs[\"threshold\"] = 0.3 # threshold (relative to the peak value)\n",
    "imfargs[\"doshift\"] = True # shifting image\n",
    "imfargs[\"shifttype\"] = \"peak\" # type of the reference\n",
    "imfargs[\"dowinmod\"] = False # clearing the brightness distribution outside the specified imaging region\n",
    "imfargs[\"imregion\"] = None # imaging region for winmod\n",
    "imfargs[\"doconv\"] = True # convolve the image with a Gaussian\n",
    "imfargs[\"convprm\"] = beamprm # parameter for Gaussian convolution\n",
    "imfargs[\"save_totalflux\"] = False # keep totalflux while editing images"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Run imaging."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 46,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {

     "output_type": "stream",
